Dennis: In my 1986 NZOI memoir I illustrated two species, one called D. spicata and one called D. spicata. Regrettably, my IDs were based on MacGillivray's illustrations in the Prodromus, NOT Busk (1852), who described the species. Dimetopia cornuta is OK, being was correctly identified by me (and MacGillivray) but MacGillivray's illustration of D. spicata (and mine) differ in having a horizontal opesia whereas Busk's spicata has an oblique opesia. So MacGillivray's and my spicata is either a new species or this species or Busk's species = D. barbata, a senior subjective synonym. When I'm back in my office in the morning I need to check d'Hondt's description of barbata.

Further to all this is NIWA 88722. The opesia and spine arrangement suggest this is yet another species - undescribed, and a total surprise as I don't think I've seen it before.

Dennis email 14.1.2020: Hincksina sp(p.?) BLEED 61, 178: Several years ago, Kevin Tilbrook initiated a small project to clarify the status of the various Gregarinidra (Flustridae) species in Australasia. We collaborated and exchanged SEMs, some obtained by Kevin from Mary Spencer Jones. In 2013 Kevin wrote a draft ms (Tilbrook & Gordon) in which he distinguished six Australian species of Gregarinidra sensu lato [ G. denticulata (Busk, 1852), G. inermis (Busk, 1852),  G. quadricornis (MacGillivray, 1860), G. serrata (MacGillivray, 1869), with two more, inarmata Hincks, 1881 and a new species, separated as a new genus.] He also discriminated three New Zealand species, all new – one from the Kermadec Ridge, one from Fiordland and another from Cook Strait (but widespread). Complicating things is the fact that Phil Bock (BHP, WoRMS) attributes two of the Australian species (denticulata, inermis) to the European genus Hincksinoflustra Prenant & Bobin, 1961 and Bjorn Berning (in correspondence) synonymises Gregarinidra Barroso, 1949 with Hincksina Norman, 1949! We have done nothing with the ms since, hoping that Bjorn would write a definitive ms convincing us of the synonymy of the European type species of Hincksina  and Gregarinidra [not to mention Hincksinoflustra], and gene sequencing would no doubt help. There is somewhat of an impasse here. Nothing has been done on our ms since; Kevin got sidelined from science and I have been sidelined by numerous other projects

Dennis email 14.1.2020: The illustrated specimen is puzzling. I immediately thought A. perforata because this species tends to have its perforations in sectors, which is not typically the case in A. unicornis [but see BLEED 221 images]. However, the distal rim of the orifice in perforata [assuming that I correctly identified it in the first place – I have never seen an SEM of Maplestone’s material] bears avicularia, which is not the case in this specimen. But I think you have sequenced unicornis previously, so it’s worth comparing the sequences. Arachnopusia species in New Zealand can be so variable morphologically I have often wondered how many species I am actually dealing with.

Berning check with Berlin:"I have heard back from Frankfurt/Berlin today and got SEM images of the types of the Adeonas that Kirchenpauer introduced in 1880.
Just one match, unfortunately: BLEED 297+298 is Adeona foliifera fascialis rather than A. cf. cellulosa. Both specimens share the cryptocystal denticles in the proximal avicularian opesia, and both the orifice and the avicularium seems to be shorter in relation to zooid size than in the specimen of A. cellulosa figured on the BryozoaHomepage. Moreover, whereas A. cellulosa is reported from southeastern Australia, A. foliifera fascialis and BLEED 297+298 are from the Western Australian shelf (from off Carnarvon south to Abrolhos).
I have attached some images so you can see for yourself.
 
Adeona albida, arborescens, intermedia and macrothyris are all distinctly different from our specimens (only the latter is relatively close to A. foliifera fascialis based on zooidal characters but since Kirchenpauer himself separated them they’re apparently distinct species)."

Email from Russell 6.8.2021: "
1. BLEED387 is back and names are updated to the last version universally. However I now see why we removed 387. Microporella_sp_BLEED11 is basically a duplicate and represents the genes from the Emily thesis (and microporella/fenestrulina paper), whilst 387 is the entire mitogenome (which she completed later) and the 18s sequence. As to why this is called Microporella_sp_BLEED11 here I have no good explanation for, especially as it is 387 in NCBI as well, but it does mean it has to be removed. note:
Qubit= = 120

Original id was Buffonellaria turbata but this is not sequenced.

Mali said "694: Dette er en stein med en annen stor cheilostome til stede (20%). Det er også en Eurystomella som fouler denne cheilostomen" 
Mali "694: Her er det en Rhynchozoon jeg har tatt bilder av og det er også det vi har fått av DNA (selv om vi egentlig skulle hatt en annen art. Ihvertfall bra at bilder og sekvenser samsvarer, men må ta bedre bilder av kolonien hvis vi skal ha en sjanse til å identifisere denne."
Mali: "694 er en Rhynchozoon (også forventet)"

MHR:2001.BLEED694: Dennis: This could be Rhynchozoon angulatum (Levinsen, 1909), which was first described from Stewart Island; hence it should be discriminated genetically from R. zealandicum (BLEED 127). The uncertainty concerning the angulatum identity is the weak development of the avicularia in the SEMs, but the locality is spot on. The species lacks an aviculiferous ‘mucronate process’ above the sinus, such as is found in R. zealandicum (and many other Rhynchozoon species).

From: "Javier Souto-Derungs" <javier.souto-derungs@univie.ac.at>

Subject: Re: Specimen in Lee Hsiang tree

Yes, this sample is a new species of Robertsonidra. I have big colonies growing on kelp from the Vema seamount. I hope to finish the paper to send to publish during January. As I told to Lee Hsiang some of the species of the SEAFO campaign are new species.
Will it be included in a paper?
Do you know if this samples work properly for sequencing. As I told them, I have not information about the quality of the ethanol, I had not taken part in this campaign and I don’t know how samples were fixed, (theoretically only in ethanol).

Please tell me if you need to know anything more about the samples.

groups with a Robertsonidra.
Thanks a lot!
Cheers
Emanuela

identified in field as Chaperia sp.? by Dennis

Dennis email 24.1.2020 "BLEED.800: Chaperiopsis n. sp. In the past I have called this C. cervicornis, following previous authors. It can have up to eight oral spines, some quite thin. The transverse avicularium characterises the species complex, which has been accorded a very wide austral distribution, even to subantarctic waters, but there is considerable variability and the New Zealand form is not conspecific with that in Australia. Brown (1952, p. 113 notes that the nominal type specimen in NHM (1854.11.15.218, from Tasmania) does not appear to be that figured by Busk (1854, pl. 100, fig. 3; Busk cites no locality), but Phil Bock’s SEM photo on BHP of a specimen from Bass Strait [http://www.bryozoa.net/cheilostomata/chaperiidae/chapcer.html] looks just like Busk’s illustration."

We sequenced two species here, we have cervicoris in the SEM (and there is no ore material)

WS notes from Hanna
:For the White Sea locations, the group of us who attended the White Sea Field Course would have either dredged or collected intertidally, pooled the material from that location, and brought it to the lab. So, the "collectors" would be the lot of us from that course. I can get you names if need be. For IDs, "HLM/WSBS (White Sea Biological Station)" were identified by me, with the ID confirmed by either Olga Kotenko or Natalia Shunatova, both staff at the field station. The samples IDed by OK were done by Olga alone. As she distributed material for the ID portion of the course, she would set aside new species for me to pass along to you.

The Cribriliina annulata listed without a station number was one of those samples that Olga put aside. She didn't give me a station number, so it could be from any of the four locales. I'm guessing 😬  the two Chaperiopsis-like samples without any info are of the same ilk, but can't be sure.

"WS-02" is from 66.324 N, 33.545 E. We dredged from a rowboat just off the teeny island nearby. I'd be guessing on the depth, maybe 20-30 m? The collections were very much analog, no depth sounders or anything.

LV Parasmittina aleutensis Soule & Soule, 2002 


Piotr. "There is one species which puzzled me a bit. Its name is Parasmittina_aleutensis_BLEED942 – marked in yellow in attached Excel file. I do not know the name of the species as it is indeed different to the one I know from Svalbard. But it was collected on Svalbard (North Atlantic) and its name suggests it is something which was described in North Pacific. I cannot find reference for it therefore type material images but whoever put a name on it should double check this."

Ho Emanuela,
 
To use this ID, I checked the lectotype of trispinosa selected by Brown (I agree with you that it's not the same species), and another type (one of those is P. aleutensis).
I attached the pdf of Soule & Soule (2002), with the original description. We have checked some material deposited at the Smithisonian (MSc of Jamile), identified by Osburn, but unfortunately, we have no SEMs of these specimens (only data in my notes).
Comparing the descriptions and SEM provided by Soule and Soule, I can't see any differences between BLEED942 and auletaensis. If there is question in this identification (also due the distance between type locality of P. auletaensis and  sampling area of BLEED942), could we refer it as Parasmittina cf. aleutensis (agree that it's best because we have no ovicells to be sure about the identity of BLEED942).
 
Best, Leandro
 
 
Em ter., 18 de mai. de 2021 às 04:43, Emanuela Di Martino <e.d.martino@nhm.uio.no> escreveu:
Hi Leandro,
 
I have a query about BLEED942 in the big tree. It is a Parasmittina (small fragment), initially named P. trispinosa (which was not convincing). You IDed it as P. aleutensis, and not believing myself it was a real trispinosa I accepted your ID. I have to say that I am not familiar with P. aleutensis and I don’t have the pdf in which it was described. Piotr, who was the collector, raised the concern that I quote below:
 
“There is one species which puzzled me a bit. Its name is Parasmittina_aleutensis_BLEED942 – marked in yellow in attached Excel file. I do not know the name of the species as it is indeed different to the one I know from Svalbard. from Wayne: Microporella_hyadesi_BLEED956 —>  Flustramorpha flabellaris_BLEED956
(This is not M. hyadesi. Your SEM of the specimen is consistent with Flustramorpha flabellaris (Busk, 1854) - as in Hayward and Cook 1983 see page 83-84. A species only reported from South Africa. Marcus 1922 refered it to Microporella but Hayward and Cook 1983 refered it to Flustromorpha giving no rationale and no full description. I agree that the specimen should be refered to Microporella and that it is consistent with M. flabellaris (not M. hyadesi) based on the shape of the orifice, position of the avicularium in relation to the ascophore and the orientation of its palate that is consistently parallel to the frontal plane. Interestingly in your tree it has a close affinity to Flustramorpha angusta also from South Africa. Perhaps Dennis could comment.) Updated 24.6.2021

DPG identified as Schizomavella aeoteraroa in the field, but SEM looks like Calytotheca (send for confirmation)

EDM: it is in Calyptotheca position and looks like a Calyptotheca (also in Gordon 1989)

From: Dennis Gordon <Dennis.Gordon@niwa.co.nz> Date: Saturday, 25 April 2020 at 00:08 To: Emanuela Di Martino <e.d.martino@nhm.uio.no> Subject: RE: ID confirmation for three taxa in the big tree
 
Dear Emanuela
 
BLEED1112 is indeed Schizomavella aotearoa. BUT, I really don’t know what genus this is. I didn’t want to put up yet another new monotypic genus when I described the species in 1989, so opted for Schizoporella, which it clearly isn’t. Later, because of the ovicell, which I came to recognise as ‘smittinoid’, I transferred it Schizomavella (see Gordon et al. 2009) which again it clearly isn’t. Lanceoporidae, which includes Calyptotheca, is close to Bitectiporidae, in which I would include ‘S.’ aotearoa; Stephanotheca is a genus that morphologically blurs the boundaries between the two families, at least as argued persuasively by Reverter-Gil, Souto & Fernández-Pulpeiro, 2012. I would not include ‘S.’ aotearoa in Calyptotheca – the gene tree may correctly show topological proximity to Calyptotheca, but I assume the tree doesn’t have enough taxa in it to be definitive. Unless ‘S.’ aotearoa actually nests well within Calyptotheca, I think a new genus may well be appropriate for it.

BB: This one is different from N. tenella. I've taken some measurements: this species differs in having distinctly shorter zooids (c. 340 µm) and opesiae (250) than the type of N. tenella (460 and 330), which I took images of a couple of years ago. And while opesium width is roughly the same (120 vs. 130), the zooids are more closely space, i.e. there is less proximal gymnocyst developed in this species. I'd therefore give it as N. aff. tenella. EDM leave it

DEnnis email: 24.1.2020:"BLEED.1540: Puellina vicariata (Waters, 1923). Rosso et al. (2018) argued that the subgenera of Puellina should be made genera, so we should now attribute this species to Cribrilaria. I think it’s too soon to make the call so I’m sticking with Puellina. Based on recent literature (notably Tilbrook et al. 2001, Tilbrook 2006), this Singaporean species falls more or less within the morphological range of P. egretta Ryland & Hayward, 1992 from the Great Barrier Reef. There are some minor differences, but whether these are population-level or not is unclear. It’s good that we have material for sequencing. Having said that, there is a little-known species that may actually be a senior synonym of egretta (or very similar to it) and this should be checked out by comparing type material. It is Puellina vicariata (Waters, 1923). Waters stressed the commonness of vicarious kenozooids. These look like autozooids but lack an orifice. They are common in some Singaporean material I examined by SEM last year (back in Wellington). Further, Waters described the avicularium as very long, and that is also the case. Also, Waters’s material came from “Singapore or Philippines”.  All things considered, I think we can call our species P. vicariata. I included this species name in the Tilbrook & Gordon (2016) list based on Harmer’s mention of it (under a different name - radiata)."

note:
Previously ided as "Arbocuspis bellula?" by Dennis.

 EDM email 11.5.2021 to LV:

We had BLEED249 for long time just as Electridae sp. until I discussed with Dennis and we decided to go for Arbocuspis bellula. Dennis’ comment was: “The nearest I can get this to is the illustration in Liu, Yin & Ma (2001) Biology of Marine-Fouling Bryozoans in the Coastal waters of China, pl. 15, which they attribute to Electra bellula, i.e. Arbocuspis,  Some of the zooids lack spines and the proximal opesial margin lacks a cusp in 1-2 zooids. I guess it depends how much variation one accepts in this species. Clearly a need for sequencing of different populations.”
 
A. bicornis slipped out of our minds given the high variability of E. bellula. But it makes much more sense now. We’ll modify the name of 1569 in the next round of name changes.

--from LV 
Dear Emanuela and Lee Hsiang,

I checked all clades and they are ok for me, excepted for two identifications below:

Arbocuspis_bellula_BLEED1569
Electridae_sp_BLEED249

In the tree, they were considered two different species, which could explain the morphological difference between these specimens. Are there genetic differences between these two species? I noted that the cards included a single identification for these two species (but they are morphologically different), as Arbocuspis bellula.

I'm also not sure about this identification. Based on morphology, this species is similar to Arbocuspis bicornis rather than Arbocuspis bellula, with type deposited at NHMUK. I included some remarks on it in my paper published in 2016: http://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4097.1.3 .

Dennis email 24.1.2020 "BLEED.1626: Chiastosella jellayae.; BLEED.1626: Chiastosella jellyae (Brown, 1952). This is a really interesting species. I have photos that Paul sent me years ago of Exochella jellyae Brown, 1952, pp. 291–293, a fossil described from Waipukurau, presumed Pliocene. Brown’s illustration of the paratype, NHM D. 32503, shows ovicells (also seen in Paul’s SEMs but the specimen is poorly preserved) that look like those of Chiastosella. The holotype, D. 1421, is better preserved and shows six oral spines and a median convexity in the orifice (unlike typical Chiastosella, which is why Brown interpreted it as Exochella. I SEMed an ovicellate Otago colony and it is Chiastosella. In short, I interpret this as the first record of Brown’s species at the present day, but now at a more southern latitude."

NOTE: this was called Exochella jellyae, Brown 1952

BB: I'd rather give it as R. cf. grimaldii as no one has revised the type yet. The notion f Hay&McK (2002) that this species occurs from the White Sea to the Mediterranean is a myth, no more. Even in the Mediterranean there are differences between the populations referred to this species: in these here the small adventitious avicularia are pointed and the large suboral ones very broad at the level of the crossbar, whereas in the ones from Croatia (Hay&McK) the small ones have rounded rostra and the large ones are much narrower proximally

From: Dennis Gordon <Dennis.Gordon@niwa.co.nz>
Date: 13 October 2021 at 00:10:38 CEST
To: Emanuela Di Martino <e.d.martino@nhm.uio.no>
Subject: Marcusadorea

﻿Hi Emanuela

The identification of Marcusadorea efatensis for a specimen (BLEED 1555) from Singapore appears to have come from Phil Bock (see message below that includes images). LH apparently posted the light-microscope images, yielding two responses, one from Phil, followed by Leandro’s comment. At the time, I had no idea what the species was. Leandro seems to have been doubtful about the attribution to Marcusadorea and I was also skeptical, though it is still possible. Perhaps the/a specimen with ovicells is still in Singapore; we need an SEM shot of the ovicell.

However, the specimen about which you enquired, i.e. BLEED 1948 from Panama, shares an impressive number of characters with Marcusadorea tubulosa (Canu & Bassler, 1928) (see attached PDF, p. 64), which inclines me to think that BLEED 1948 may indeed be a marcusadoreid, perhaps even Marcusadorea, even though it is more pseudoporous. Likewise, if BLEED 1555 groups with BLEED 1948, then perhaps both belong to Marcusadoreidae.  I think, for the purposes of your tree, you could call BLEED 1948 Marcusadorea sp. as an interim ID. But both need detailed comparative study.

Cheers, Dennis

And from Leandro
How are you?
It is nice to see that BLEED1948 groups with Marcusadorea, because it seems to be morphologically related. I agree that BLEED1948 could be assigned to Gemellitheca. See that BLEED1948 is not  a species of Rhamphostomella, because the type has lyrula (thus, I don't think it is not directly related to Marcusadoreidae). Additionally, Rhamphostomella ovata (species with sinus) is better placed in a distinct genus (maybe new) rather Rhamphostomella (the type species has lyrula, I think), but it is a work that needs to be done separately. To solve it, we need to do a complete review of other problematic genera, including Calyptotheca and Thornelya.
In my first review on the Judy's monograph, I suggested merging the name Gemelliporidridae (used in the first version) with Marcusadoreidae, but she prefer to include Gemellitheca in Bitectiporidae rather than Marcusadoreidae.

identified in field as Chaperia sp.? by Dennis

Dennis email 24.1.2020 "BLEED.800: Chaperiopsis n. sp. In the past I have called this C. cervicornis, following previous authors. It can have up to eight oral spines, some quite thin. The transverse avicularium characterises the species complex, which has been accorded a very wide austral distribution, even to subantarctic waters, but there is considerable variability and the New Zealand form is not conspecific with that in Australia. Brown (1952, p. 113 notes that the nominal type specimen in NHM (1854.11.15.218, from Tasmania) does not appear to be that figured by Busk (1854, pl. 100, fig. 3; Busk cites no locality), but Phil Bock’s SEM photo on BHP of a specimen from Bass Strait [http://www.bryozoa.net/cheilostomata/chaperiidae/chapcer.html] looks just like Busk’s illustration."

We sequenced two Chaperiopsis species here, we have cervicoris in the SEM (and there is no ore material)

Email from Russell 6.8.2021: "
1. BLEED387 is back and names are updated to the last version universally. However I now see why we removed 387. Microporella_sp_BLEED11 is basically a duplicate and represents the genes from the Emily thesis (and microporella/fenestrulina paper), whilst 387 is the entire mitogenome (which she completed later) and the 18s sequence. As to why this is called Microporella_sp_BLEED11 here I have no good explanation for, especially as it is 387 in NCBI as well, but it does mean it has to be removed. This only affects the alignments and the SI1 and 2 figures, so is easy to fix. It has no bearing for BISSE or MCMCTREE and as the names are updated here for the others these can now be run again.
